Indonesia Stocks: Medco Energi, Indo Tambangraya Megah, Timah

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-05-16T05:22:31Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-16/indonesia-stocks-medco-energi-indo-tambangraya-megah-timah.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the noon Jakarta-time break.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  retreated 39.97 points, or 1
percent, to 3,792.05, set for the steepest drop since March 17.
The market is closed tomorrow for a public holiday.  Coal producers: PT Tambang Batubara Bukit Asam (PTBA IJ), a
state-coal mining company, dropped 3 percent to 20,750 rupiah
and PT Borneo Lumbung Energi & Metal (BORN IJ) plunged 4.9
percent to 1,550 rupiah. PT Indo Tambangraya Megah (ITMG IJ),
the Indonesian unit of  Thailand ’s biggest coal producer, Banpu
Pcl, fell 2.5 percent to 44,800 rupiah. The three stocks were
the biggest drags on the Jakarta Mining Index.  Power-station coal  prices  at  Australia ’s Newcastle port, an
Asian benchmark, fell 3.2 percent to $118.74 a metric ton in the
week ended May 13, according to the  globalCOAL NEWC Index .  PT Energi Mega Persada (ENRG IJ), the nation’s second-
largest listed oil company, fell 3.9 percent to 197 rupiah, set
for the steepest drop since Jan. 20. The stock fell on
speculation last week’s 28 percent rally was overdone, according
to Raditya Christian Artono, an analyst at PT Mandiri Sekuritas.  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ),  Indonesia ’s
biggest listed oil company, lost 2.7 percent to 2,675 rupiah,
set for the steepest drop since Feb. 22. Crude oil for June
delivery fell as much as 1.4 percent to $98.26 a barrel in
after-hours trading in  New York , declining for the first time in
three days.  PT Samudera Indonesia (SMDR IJ), Indonesia’s second-largest
shipping company, gained 1.2 percent to 4,275 rupiah, on course
for the highest close since April 12. Samudera has allocated 1.5
trillion rupiah ($175 million) for this year’s capital
expenditure to support expansion plans, Kontan reported, citing
Asmari Herry Prayitno, the company’s operational director.
Prayitno couldn’t be reached when called at his office.  PT Timah (TINS IJ), Indonesia’s biggest tin producer, lost
3.7 percent to 2,600 rupiah, set for the sharpest decline since
Jan. 10. Tin futures retreated 2.4 percent to $28,600 a metric
ton in  London  on May 13, the lowest close since March 16.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
